    <body>
        <sect1>
            <title>Laser Guns and Spaceships</title>

            <para>
                <tm>YAGS SciFi</tm> is a science fiction roleplaying game system designed
                for playing characters in a galaxy spanning empire, where mighty space
                fleets can battle in the depths of space and explorers can explore strange
                new worlds each week, without having to spend centuries in travel. The 
                rules of Newton and Einstein still (mostly) apply, except where they need
                to be bent, twisted or outright broken in order to allow for all of the
                above.
            </para>
            
            <image src="images/ship_planet.png" width="85mm" height="40mm" align="center"/>

            <para>
                It is the type of science fiction where humans (or at least, blue furry 
                creatures that act very much like humans) are still the stars of the story.
                Aliens are understandable, and computers are tools that made things easier
                for people, but don't replace them. AI may exist, but it is limited, and
                people live (mostly) in the bodies that they were born with, rather than
                uploading their consciousness into machines or whole new bodies. If androids
                exist, then they are either rare, illegal or limited in what they can do.
            </para>
            
            <para>
                So though technology has advanced well beyond what is possible today, the
                advances are mostly in the form of mechanical engineering, rather than
                software and nanotech. Giant starships can ferry people between star systems
                at greater than the speed of light, or fight great space battles at ranges
                of thousands of kilometres. Cities may float above the clouds of gas giants,
                or beneath the seas of ocean worlds. Within such cities, flying cars, 
                holographic advertising displays and personal communication devices will be
                a common sight.
            </para>
            
            <para>
                This is the science fiction of <e>Babylon 5</e>, <e>Aliens</e> or
                <e>Ringworld</e>. It does not claim to be <e>hard</e>, but neither is it 
                space fantasy where science and scale are regularly ignored for no reason.
            </para>
            
            <sect2>
                <title>Assumptions</title>

                <para>
                    The sort of assumptions that are made by these rules concern
                    the type of technology available, and the type of societies
                    that Player Characters will come from, can be summed up as
                    follows:
                </para>

                <itemlist order="strict">
                    <item name="Human centric">
                        Many people within the campaign are human, or at least human enough
                        such that they don't require special rules. Aliens can range from 
                        non-existant or rare, to reasonably common. However, they are 
                        generally understandable by humans and not utterly exotic.
                    </item>

                    <item name="Star Spanning Empire">
                        Most of humanity is spread across a single empire that spans tens
                        of thousands of star systems, and travel between these systems is
                        relatively common and cheap.
                    </item>

                    <item name="Jump drives">
                        FTL travel is by a jump drive or hyperspace technology
                        which can travel a few light years a day. FTL communication 
                        faster than this may or may not be possible.
                    </item>

                    <item name="Meat space">
                        Something prevents run away computing power in the
                        early 21st century, making true AIs very rare, and
                        reducing the effects of Cyberspace realities. Humans are
                        needed to fly spaceships, fire weapons and generally go
                        out and do things.
                    </item>
                    
                    <item name="Super Efficient Space Drives">
                        There are no reactionless drives (or at least, they are
                        sufficiently high tech to be beyond what is commonly available),
                        but what there is would be considered magical by today's standards.
                        It's possible to cross a typical solar system in days to weeks.
                    </item>
                    
                    <item name="Psionics">
                        There may or may not be Psionics, or the ability to
                        manipulate reality with the mind. This could be limited to
                        plain old telepathy, or allow for more exotic abilities.
                    </item>
                </itemlist>

                <para>
                    These assumptions are designed to allow star spanning heroic
                    fiction, not totally unlike that found in certain classic
                    RPG systems from the 1970s, or similar to TV SciFi shows such
                    as <e>Babylon 5</e>, <e>Firefly</e> or <e>Farscape</e>. High
                    technology is possible, and it is possible to centre a
                    campaign on who has the biggest and best equipment, but people
                    are still needed to control that equipment. Computers are
                    regulated to making life easier, rather than dominating the story.
                </para>
                
                <sect3>
                    <title>Known Space</title>
                    
                    <para>
                        The campaign itself is assumed to be set in a more or less unified
                        empire, which has some degree of stability.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
            
            <sect2>
                <title>Technology</title>
                
                <para>
                    In a galaxy spanning civilisation, the level of available technology is
                    not evenly distributed, and whilst the core worlds may have cities floating
                    in the skies, and instant regrowth of lost body parts, the outer colonies
                    may still be struggling at the pre-industrial level.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    Trade happens though, and useful tools will find their way to even the
                    most backward worlds. Just as mobile phones are crucial to the life of
                    people in developing countries today, even a feudal society may find it
                    useful to equip the royal guard with laser guns, and to rent the use of
                    weather satillites in return for gold.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    As such, you should expect a range of technology being used wherever you
                    are in the galaxy. Items which are durable and don't require an understanding
                    of how they work to be able to use them are welcome everywhere.
                </para>
                
                <sect3>
                    <title>Technology Levels</title>
                    
                    <para>
                        <tm>YAGS SciFi</tm> details the progress of technology from the modern
                        day (TL 8) until the edges of the impossible (TL 17), but really works
                        best in the range of TL 13 - 16, where interstellar travel is fast and
                        easy.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        The following overview describes the different levels of technology from
                        the point of how it affects a possible campaign, and the characters
                        within it.
                    </para>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 7 - The Atomic Age</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            This is the technological equivalent of the third quarter of the
                            20th century, from the 1940s until about 1980. It is the start of
                            the computer age, of commercial jet engines and mass communication.
                            It is also the start of the atomic age, and of space travel.
                        </para>
                        
                        <para>
                            The technology available here could get people into space, but it's
                            hard and expensive, and not conducive to a galaxy spanning campaign.
                            It is probably the highest level of technology possible mechanically
                            though, and probably common on a lot of small colony worlds.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 8 - The Digital Age</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            Equivalent to technology between 1980 and 2020. Computers and
                            personal communication come to dominate. Space technology and
                            exploration also becomes a lot more practical.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 9 - Interplanetary</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            This is the level of technology beyond what is available in the
                            real world, up to maybe 2100. It assumes that interplanetary space
                            travel becomes possible and practical for humans, with limited 
                            colonisation of other worlds. The rate of change in computer 
                            technology begins to slow, if not come to a halt, but energy 
                            storage becomes a lot denser, safer and more efficient, allowing
                            for advanced mobile devices which last weeks on a single charge.
                            Medical technology continues to advance.
                        </para>
                        
                        <para>
                            This is about the minimum level of technology practical for a SciFi
                            campaign, but options can be quite limited in scope.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 10-11 - Interstellar</title>
                    
                        <para>
                            Interstellar travel becomes possible, and campaigns set at this
                            level will have limited travel between the stars. Fusion power
                            becomes a lot more efficient and prevalent, bodily organs can be
                            regrown, and lasers and particle beams become common weapons.
                        </para>
                        
                        <para>
                            At this point exploration of alien star systems is still slow and
                            expensive, so may be good for a campaign of exploration where the
                            players are amongst the few exploring new worlds. There is likely
                            to be a wild frontier mentality, with colonists laying claim to
                            worlds and hoping for independence. Large corporations
                            and governments may well have other ideas.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 12-13 - Galactic Empires</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            This is a new age of exploration and discovery as interstellar
                            traveller becomes faster, cheaper and more reliable. Repulsor
                            fields come onto the scene, making 'anti-gravity' vehicles
                            possible. This is a good time for the formation and expansion of
                            galactic empires.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 14-15 - The</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            By this point fast interstellar travel is the norm.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 16-17 - The Limits of the Possible</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            This is the maximum level of technology for most galactic empire
                            campaigns. It may be available in the core worlds, but will probably
                            not be seen much beyond these.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>TL 18+ - The Impossible</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            This level of technology may be possessed by advanced alien
                            civilisations, but it is really beyond the scope of these rules.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>
                
                <sect3>
                    <title>Common Tech</title>
                    
                    <para>
                        Though there is a wide range of technology levels across civilised
                        space, galactic trade ensures that there are some high tech goods which
                        can be pretty much assumed to be anywhere. These will generally be built
                        by TL 15+ worlds, but available for sale in all C class or better space 
                        ports at least, if not on the high streets of worlds that are open to
                        interplanetary trade.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        The costs of such goods are pretty stable, with variations only really
                        being noticeable towards the edges of known space.
                    </para>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Communications</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            Radio is the standard form of communication across large distances
                            in space, but short-range personal communication tends to use N-wave
                            comms. These are built into hand-sized communicators which act much
                            like a TL-8 'smart phone', except they last over a week of heavy
                            use on a single charge (up to a month with light use), and have a
                            communication range of up to a hundred kilometres, which is 
                            transparent to pretty much anything.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            In populated regions, this is routed through communication stations
                            (similar to mobile phone masts in TL-8), allow world-wide 
                            communications, even if in a building or underground.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            Larger units extend range to up to one thousand kilometres. Most
                            ships will have one, especially shuttles or other ships designed to
                            land on wilderness worlds. Personal comms then route through the
                            shuttle's more powerful unit to allow communication with orbital
                            ships. Most populated worlds with a C+ star port will have full
                            world coverage via a satellite system.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            Small, discrete units have a range of about 1km, and are generally
                            used for local comms within an assault team.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            N-wave communications are heavily encrypted, and can make heavy
                            use of rapid 'frequency' hopping that makes them difficult to
                            detect or jam in low data (audio or especially text) modes.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            They provide accurate 3D positioning on any world with full
                            coverage, and limited accuracy on worlds with more limtied
                            coverage.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>Firearms</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            The most common personal firearms are 5mm gauss weapons. They are
                            cheap, reliable and deadly. Rifles may be gauss or laser. The latter
                            are less poweful, but much more accurate, especially at range.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
            
            <sect2>
                <title>Galactic Citizens</title>
                
                <para>
                    Character generation in <tm>YAGS</tm> is based around a point buy
                    system, so you can build any sort of character that you wish, within
                    reason. The assumption though is that your character is a part of
                    galactic culture, with familiarity of space travel and high technology,
                    even if you haven't necessarily experienced it first hand yourself.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    In order for a roleplaying game to be successful, player characters
                    need to have a reason for wanting to go and do the sort of dangerous
                    things that make for a good adventure. To this end, it helps to have
                    an idea of the type of adventures the group is expecting to have, so
                    that everyone's character can be designed to want to participate.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    There are many different types of campaigns, and
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    <s>Traders</s>. You have a starship and some money, and wish to make
                    more money, generally by buying low and selling high. Such campaigns
                    often involve <e>complications</e> to make life just that little bit
                    more exciting. A variation involves smuggling or dealing with illegal
                    goods, which is higher risk put has potentially higher rewards.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    <s>Military</s>. A military campaign involves you being part of a
                    larger organisation (maybe the Imperial military), and taking on
                    missions as directed by your superiors. There may not be much room for
                    flexibility in what you do, since you have to obey orders, but you are
                    backed by an organisation which can provide guns and other equipment as
                    needed, so gives the opportunity to try out cool hardware without having
                    to buy (or steal) it.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    <s>Mercenaries</s>. Similar to a military campaign, but you are freelancers
                    who get to pick your own missions. Riskier but you have more control over
                    your destiny. Whether you work for 'good causes' or anyone who pays is
                    up to you, and complications can always make the latter seem like the
                    former.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    <s>Explorers</s>. You have a starship and want to explore the uncharted
                    parts of the galaxy, mapping new worlds and contacting alien civilisations.
                    You may be part of some government backed scout service, belong to a
                    university, or may simply be freelance archaeologissts looking to loot
                    other worlds and sell artefacts to the highest bidder.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    <s>Scoundrals</s>. You operate on the wrong side of the law. Maybe you
                    perform heists, stealing expensive goods from the secure dwellings of the
                    rich and powerful. Maybe it's scams where you con people out of their
                    earnings. Or maybe you just act as thugs and enforcers for criminal gangs
                    within a cluster of star systems. The choice is up to you. Until you get
                    caught.
                </para>
                
                <sect3>
                    <title>The Rules In Brief</title>
                    
                    <para>
                        <tm>YAGS</tm> uses a single twenty sided die (d20) for pretty much
                        everything. As with many RPG systems, players determine success or
                        failure by rolling a die and comparing it to their character's skills.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        In <tm>YAGS</tm>, a skill check needs to equal or exceed a target
                        number (TN), which is often 20. They get a bonus to the dice roll
                        equal to an attribute multiplied by their skill level. For example,
                        to drive a car, they multiply their <t>Dexterity</t> attribute and 
                        <t>Drive</t> skill together, then roll and add 1d20.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        The human average for an attribute is 3, and a professional level of
                        skill is 4, so a typical skilled driver would roll 3 x 4 (12) + d20.
                    </para>
                    
                    <sect4>
                        <title>Attributes</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            There are 8 primary attributes to define, and all
                            begin with a score of 3 (which is average for an
                            adult human). The minimum for any attribute is 2,
                            the maximum is 8, though anything above 5 is
                            considered to be <e>very</e> exceptional.
                        </para>

                        <itemlist order="strict">
                            <item name="Strength (S)">
                                How strong you are, including your ability to
                                lift and hurt things. If you have a high
                                strength then you will tend to be larger as
                                well.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Health (H)">
                                A measure of your physical fitness and stamina.
                                Health is used in checks to remain alive after
                                being seriously wounded.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Agility (A)">
                                Your agility represents your quickness, athletic
                                prowess and balance. It is used for brawling,
                                wrestling, sneaking, reaction tests and acrobatics.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Dexterity (D)">
                                Dexterity is your hand-eye coordination,
                                sleight-of-hand and skill with melee weapons.
                                Pistols also use dexterity, and rifles may
                                use dexterity or perception.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Perception (P)">
                                How alert you are, and the general quality of
                                your senses. If perceptive, you are good at
                                hiding and noticing things. Rifles and larger
                                weapons use perception.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Intelligence (I)">
                                A measure of your wit, cunning, memory and
                                intuition. Knowledges are based on intelligence,
                                as are logic and reasoning skills.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Empathy (E)">
                                Empathy is your ability to understand others.
                                It is used to make friends, convince people
                                emotionally, or to tell if someone is lying to
                                you. Empathy doesn't affect your intentions
                                to be nice or nasty, but does affect how well
                                you notice other people's feelings.
                            </item>

                            <item name="Will (W)">
                                Your Will is a measure of mental fortitude,
                                being used to resist psi, instincts and
                                emotions. A high Will makes you a good liar,
                                a low Will means you are gullible and likely
                                to give in to fear, lust and greed.
                            </item>
                        </itemlist>
                    </sect4>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Skills</title>

                        <para>
                            Skills are abilities which are gained through study, experience and
                            training. There are 8 basic skills (called <e>talents</e>) which all
                            begin at a score of 2, all other skills are assumed to start at zero
                            unless stated otherwise for your background.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            A skill of 4-5 is considered to be a trained professional, 6-7
                            is an expert, 8-11 is elite and 12+ is a true master of the
                            profession. Skills above 15 are pretty much unheard of. The 
                            maximum that a player character can start with is 10.
                        </para>

                        <sect5>
                            <title>Techniques</title>

                            <para>
                                Techniques are specialities bought within a
                                particular skill. They enable you to perform actions
                                that would be impossible or hard without it, or
                                grant a bonus in certain situations (sometimes to
                                related skills).
                            </para>
                        </sect5>
                    </sect4>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Advantages</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            <e>Advantages</e> and <e>Disadvantages</e> can only be purchased at
                            character generation time, and may describe your character's
                            background, or some inherent abilities that your character has.
                            Though they can't be purchased after character generation, some may
                            be gained in play through other means.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>
        
        <sect1>
            <title>Creating a Character</title>
            
            <para>
                Galactic citizens don't spring from nowhere, they have a background which
                defines who they are and what they can do. The first part of character
                generation consists of deciding on what that background is. 
            </para>
            
            <para>
                It is assumed that you have grown up part of galactic culture. Though you
                many have never left your home planet, or grew up on a single space station,
                you have been part of the culture and technology available to the rest of
                the galaxy. 
            </para>
            
            <para>
                Much like someone living in a rural village in Europe still has a mobile phone,
                watches the latest Hollywood films and reads the daily world news, a person
                living on a world with a pre-spaceflight civilisation still sees the drive flares
                of the starships which trade with them, they here the news from distant worlds
                and get to watch films set in the glittering cloud cities of the core worlds.
            </para>
            
            <para>
                Consumer technology is useful everywhere, so just like farmers in rural Africa
                use mobile phones to access bank accounts or check the internet for crop prices,
                so people on low tech worlds will have access to the same digital assistants and
                mobile communications that those in high tech worlds do. They might not have
                the very latest models, and they may favour those that fall back to old
                fashioned electromagnetic signals, but they're common enough that pretty much
                everyone is at least aware of what is possible.
            </para>
            
            
            <sect2>
                <title>Background Packages</title>
                
                <para>
                    Each package may provide a set of skills and attributes that you can add
                    to your character. Sometimes the package will provide an option between
                    two or more choices.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    Every character begins with a score of 3 in all attributes. They also
                    begin with a score of 2 in each of their talents - basic skills which
                    everyone has. Everything else is assumed to start at zero.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    Attribute modifiers provided as part of a package stack with all others.
                    If two packages provide +1 strength, then you will have a strength of 5.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    Skills don't stack directly. Skills will be provided at either a level of
                    two or three. If you gain a skill of two, and you already have a skill of
                    two, then it becomes three. If your skill is already three or higher, than
                    gaining a skill of two has no further effect.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    If you gain a skill of four, then it replaces an existing skill of three
                    or less. If you already have a skill of four or higher, then you instead
                    gain +1 in that skill, though this cannot increase a skill beyond eight.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    Regardless of skill level, whenever you get a duplicate skill you will
                    gain one technique in that skill.
                </para>
                
                <y:packages title="Universal Background">
                    <y:package name="Citizen of the Galaxy">
                        <description xmlns="http://yagsbook.sourceforge.net/xml">
                            <para>
                                Everyone who is part of the galactic culture starts with these
                                skills. The sector knowledge skill they select will be based on
                                their home sector, and their local language will be a language
                                spoken on their world or nearby.
                            </para>
                        </description>
                        
                        <y:skills>
                            <y:skill name="Speak (Galanglic)" score="4"/>
                            <y:skill name="Speak (Local language)" score="4"/>
                            <y:skill name="Knowledge (Known Space)" score="2"/>
                            <y:skill name="Knowledge (Sector *)" score="2"/>
                        </y:skills>
                    </y:package>
                </y:packages>

                <para>
                    Everyone gets a basic background package. Choose one.
                </para>
                
                <y:packages title="Backgrounds">
                    <description xmlns="http://yagsbook.sourceforge.net/xml">
                        <para>
                            Choose one of these which represent what skills
                            you picked up during your childhood.
                        </para>
                    </description>

                    <y:package name="Athlete">
                        <description xmlns="http://yagsbook.sourceforge.net/xml">
                            <para>
                                During your childhood you excelled at athletics, and was
                                probably a member of a local sports team. You didn't do
                                so well on the academic side however.
                            </para>
                        </description>
                        
                        <y:attributes>
                            <y:attribute name="Health" score="+1"/>
                            <y:attribute name="Intelligence" score="-1"/>
                        </y:attributes>
                        
                        <y:skills>
                            <y:skill name="Athletics" score="4"/>
                            <y:skill name="Throw" score="4"/>
                            <y:skill name="Sport" score="4"/>
                            <y:choice>
                                <y:skill name="Leadership" score="2"/>
                                <y:skill name="Brawl" score="4"/>
                            </y:choice>
                        </y:skills>
                    </y:package>
                    
                    <y:package name="Geek">
                        <description xmlns="http://yagsbook.sourceforge.net/xml">
                            <para>
                                Your were a geek with an interest in science and technology,
                                though weren't as gifted physically.
                            </para>
                        </description>
                        
                        <y:attributes>
                            <y:attribute name="Intelligence" score="+1"/>
                            <y:attribute name="Strength" score="-1"/>
                        </y:attributes>
                        
                        <y:skills>
                            <y:skill name="Netiquette" score="4"/>
                            <y:skill name="Research" score="2"/>
                            <y:skill name="Mathematics" score="2"/>
                            <y:choice>
                                <y:skill name="Computing" score="2"/>
                                <y:skill name="Electronics" score="2"/>
                            </y:choice>
                            <y:choice>
                                <y:skill name="Science" score="2"/>
                                <y:skill name="Mechanics" score="2"/>
                            </y:choice>
                        </y:skills>
                    </y:package>
                    
                    <y:package name="Street kid">
                        <description xmlns="http://yagsbook.sourceforge.net/xml">
                            <para>
                                You lived on the streets, and were probably either an orphan
                                or grew up as part of a poor family. Even if you were never a
                                criminal, you knew plenty of people who were.
                            </para>
                        </description>
                        
                        <y:attributes>
                            <y:choice>
                                <y:attribute name="Dexterity" score="+1"/>
                                <y:attribute name="Perception" score="+1"/>
                            </y:choice>
                            <y:attribute name="Health" score="-1"/>
                        </y:attributes>
                        
                        <y:skills>
